('english', 'NECO', 'Parents encourage their children to exercise financial prudence. "Prudence" means:', 'caution', 'sincerity', 'credence', 'precision', NULL, 'A', 'The word "prudence" /pru:dns/ in the sentence means carefulness or caution in managing finances. Therefore, the word or group of words nearest in meaning to "prudence" is "caution."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Awa deceived Ahmed into handing over all his savings. "Deceived" means:', 'fooled', 'cheated', 'cooked', 'conned', NULL, 'A', 'In this sentence, the word "deceived" means to trick or mislead someone. The word nearest in meaning to "deceived" is "fooled."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'It turned out that the plaintiff''s claim was false. "Allegation" means:', 'surmise', 'contention', 'pronouncement', 'allegation', NULL, 'C', 'This means that the assertion or accusation that was found to be false is an "allegation."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The aggrieved faction held a clandestine meeting. "Clandestine" means:', 'quiet', 'secret', 'brief', 'organized', NULL, 'B', 'To hold a clandestine meeting means to hold a secret meeting, where the purpose or details are not meant to be known by others. Therefore, the word "secret" (option A) is the word nearest in meaning to "clandestine" in this sentence.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Morgan Pharmacy is the sole distributor of the antiviral drug. "Sole" means:', 'creditable', 'major', 'only', 'first', NULL, 'C', 'In this sentence, the word "sole" means "only." It emphasizes that Morgan Pharmacy is the exclusive distributor of the antiviral drug, implying that no other distributor is involved.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Police officers holding batons impounded the banker''s car. "Impounded" means:', 'damaged', 'seized', 'banned', 'collected', NULL, 'B', 'To seize something means to take possession of it forcefully or legally. In this sentence, the police officers took possession of the banker''s car, so the word "seized" is the closest in meaning to "impounded."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The English teacher is always cheerful. "Gleeful" means:', 'satisfied', 'zealous', 'gleeful', 'careful', NULL, 'C', 'In this sentence, the word "cheerful" means happy or in a good mood. Among the options provided, the word that is closest in meaning to "cheerful" is "gleeful."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The Chairman is of the opinion that laying off workers is pernicious to the growth of the company. "Pernicious" means:', 'harmful', 'relevant', 'indispensable', 'crucial', NULL, 'A', 'The word "pernicious" means causing great harm or damage. Therefore, the word that nearest in meaning to "pernicious" in this sentence is "harmful."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'It was she that commanded me to leave the room. "Ordered" means:', 'encouraged', 'persuaded', 'induced', 'commanded', NULL, 'D', 'In this sentence, the word "commanded" means that she gave a direct order or instruction for the speaker to leave the room.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The valedictorian was admired for her perseverance while at school. "Tenacity" means:', 'patience', 'humility', 'enthusiasm', 'tenacity', NULL, 'D', 'Tenacity refers to the quality of being determined and persistent in achieving a goal or completing a task. In the given sentence, the valedictorian is admired for her perseverance, which implies that she has shown determination and persistence in her studies and activities while at school. Therefore, the word "tenacity" is the closest in meaning to the underlined word "perseverance" in this context.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The fisherman said he sighted a _________ of fish in the river.', 'pack', 'Swarm', 'shoal', 'colony', NULL, 'C', 'A shoal /fʃʌl/ is a group of fish swimming together. It is a common term used to describe a large number of fish swimming together in a particular area.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The principal corrected no one else but _________.', 'me', 'I', 'she', 'myself', NULL, 'A', 'In this sentence, the objective case of the first-person singular pronoun should be used after the preposition "but." The objective form is "me," which is the appropriate choice in this context.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The thug was _________ murder.', 'sued', 'charged with', 'convicted for', 'charged for', NULL, 'B', '"When someone is charged with murder," it means that they have been formally accused of committing the crime of murder. The word "charged" here refers to the legal action taken by authorities to accuse someone of a crime.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Asokoro office _________ is located in Ibadan.', 'headquarter', 'headquarters', 'headquarters', 'headquarter''s', NULL, 'B', 'The word "headquarters" is a noun that refers to the main office or company location of an organization or company. In this case, we are talking about the headquarters of the Asokoro office.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'John should be through with his work by now, ________?', 'isn''t it', 'shouldn''t he', 'can''t he', 'didn''t he', NULL, 'B', 'The phrase "shouldn''t he" is asking for confirmation or agreement with the statement that John should be through with his work. The phrase "shouldn''t he" is used to seek agreement or confirmation in a question form.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'This is the man _________ I said told me the interesting story.', 'who', 'whom', 'whose', 'which', NULL, 'A', '"Who" introduces a relative clause that gives more information about a person. In this sentence, the relative pronoun is used as the subject of the second clause. "Who" is used to qualify a noun in the subject position, but "whom" describes a noun in object position.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The accused forgot _________ the police said.', 'what', 'that the police said', 'when the police said', 'which', NULL, 'A', '"What" is the appropriate relative pronoun in this sentence that functions as object of the verb said so we use "what" which introduces a noun clause and acts as an object.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The officer _________ is my brother.', 'on uniform', 'with uniform', 'in uniform', 'in uniform dress', NULL, 'C', '"In" is the appropriate preposition to describe the officer''s state or condition of being in a uniform. "In" is used to indicate being inside or within something.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The footballers have been practicing hard _________ in the stadium all morning.', 'in the stadium all', 'hard in the stadium all', 'all morning in the stadium', 'hard in the stadium all morning', NULL, 'B', '"Hard in the stadium all morning" is the answer choice that correctly places the adverb "hard" and the prepositional phrase "in the stadium" before the noun phrase "all morning."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Professor John is the leader of the new _________ committee to review the book.', 'fifty-man', 'fifty-men''s', 'fifty-men', 'fifty-men''s', NULL, 'A', '"Fifty-man" is a compound adjective that modifies the noun committee. A compound adjective to describe that act as a single adjective consists of two or more words joined by a hyphen.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'James appears _________ wiser than his friends.', 'more', 'most', 'much', 'very', NULL, 'C', '"Much" is an adverb that modifies the comparative adjective wiser. An adverb is a word that modifies a verb, an adjective, or another adverb by answering questions such as how, when, where, why, or to what degree.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'That world famous athlete is guilty, _________ way you look at it.', 'whichever', 'however', 'whatever', 'whenever', NULL, 'A', '"Whichever" is the correct relative pronoun used to introduce a relative clause that gives additional information about a noun or pronoun.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'We were all afraid when the alarm went off.', 'rang up', 'rang out', 'rang off', 'rang', NULL, 'B', '"Went off" is the correct answer because it is used to describe the action of an alarm sounding or activating. When an alarm "goes off," it means that it has started making noise or has been triggered.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'The Chairman wasn''t privy _________ that information.', 'to', 'about', 'of', 'for', NULL, 'A', 'The phrase "privy to" means to be allowed to know about something secret or private. So, the sentence should read: "The Chairman wasn''t privy to that information."', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'We were lucky our driver didn''t die in the accident, ________?', 'weren''t we', 'didn''t we', 'were we', 'did we', NULL, 'A', 'The verb of the sentence should be the basis for creating the tag. The verb is "were", promised, for emphatic purpose. The statement is positive, so by rule of question tag we expect a negative tag.', NULL), 
('english', 'NECO', 'Before the lecturer entered the hall, the board _________.', 'was cleaned', 'has been cleaned', 'had cleaned', 'had been cleaned', NULL, 'D', 'This is because the sentence is in the past tense, indicating that the action of cleaning the board occurred before the lecturer entered the hall. The past perfect tense "had cleaned" is used to show that the action of cleaning the board was completed before another past action (the lecturer entering the hall) took place.', NULL);
